	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Are regional advisory councils open to ACP participation?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The EU Fisheries Commissioner, Joe Borg, addressed the Norwegian School of Economics and Business Administration on the 25th February, and presented the new common fisheries policy.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> He particularly highlighted that the CFP reform meant better involvement of stakeholders in the decision-making process through the establishment of regional advisory councils (RACs).</p><p> Commissioner Borg said 'The relevant regulation on RACs states that two-thirds of the general assembly should be made up of representatives of the fishing industry and the remaining third of representatives of other interests. Additional interested parties, such as third countries, have the possibility to apply for observer status in these RACs and it is then up to the RAC itself to take a decision on whether and in which form observer status will be granted'.</p><p> Six RACs have been defined, one of them on 'distant-water fishing', which includes EU fleet activities in ACP waters.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/discours/speech58_en.htm" target="_self">Speech by Dr Joe Borg, 'Taking the CFP reforms forward - opportunities a...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> EU regional advisory councils bring together representatives of the regional fisheries sector and other stakeholders to give advice and make suggestions in relation to fisheries management. This is a platform in which a positive, even if informal, dialogue between EU operators and ACP countries could take place at a very early stage of the decision-making process.</p><p> Although the RAC on distant-water fishing is still at a preliminary stage of development, it would be advisable for interested ACP coastal countries where EU fleets are active to apply for observer status. For those interested, a formal request should be sent to the contact point of the RAC on distant-water fishing (the Spanish organisation FEOPE: 
<a href="mailto:feope@feope.com" target="_self">feope@feope.com</a> ) or to Commissioner Joe Borg.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

